jp\nJUDGE JOHN C. COHET, above.\nnow stabilization administrator,\nhas been authorized by President\nTruman to establish an entirely\nnew government wage policy\nwhich liberalizes the granting of\nwage raise*\nIts Planting Time Now for\nEVERGREENS, FLOWERING\nMx SHRUBS AND SHADE TREES\nSHADF. TREES $1.50 up\nFLOWERING SHRUBS 45c up\nFOUNDATION EVERGREENS $2.50 up\nBeautiful atock and many varietie* from\nKzJj\u00dfw w kich to chooae.\nVISIT OUR GIFT SHOP\nWe handle wall bracket*, vaiei, pottery\nand many other uteful item* for the home\nWillow Run Nurseries\nEcor.sc Road, 5 Miles East of Ypsilanti\nOoen Sunday Afternoons\nTHE YPSILANTI DAILY PRESS, YPSILANTI. MICH FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 2, 194*\nliahson W arils of (lliaiijnnj*\nLabor Market Year Ahead\nBv ROGER W. BAUSON\nBab.-on Park. .Mass., Nov. 2 1\nhave jus' returned from a confer\nence on wages. Labor was repre\nsented by a very smart lawyer,\naud management was represented\nby a Kindly employer.\nArguments for Higher Wages\n(1) Labor's lawyer stated that\nhis people had worked 40 hours a\nweek before the- war; that duriug\nthe war they had worked at hous\na week and that lor these addition\nal II hours received time-and-a-half\npay. The employer acknowledged\nthis; but stated that the boys of\nthe family were then in the Army\nand tlie family needed more in\ncome Now these boys liavo re\nj lurne-i and the family income, even\nWithout 'his overtime, win be as\ni high as it was before,\nj (2> Labor's lawyer then com\nplained about the deductions\nwhich are made from the pay en\nvclop-- namely, for Soria! Security,\ntlie purchase of bonds and the pay\nment of taxes. Tlie employer\nanewvied by saying that the deduc\ntion for Social Security was match\ned by a similar amount from him\nand that the total amount (double\nwhat was deducted front the em\nploye) is set aside for a pension.\nTherefore, it is really not a de\nduetion. The same applies to bond\npurchases. These bonds are as\ngood as money and can be cashed\nin any time. As to taxes, both\nthe*lawyer for labor and the em\nployee agreed that these would be\neliminated by the new tax bill go\nittg into effect in January. 1946.\n(3) Labor\u2019s lawyer talked about\nthe increased cost of-living. This\nwas admitted by the employer,\nbut lie presented government sta\nttstics showing that living costs as\na whole have not gone tip more\nj than the base wage has risen\nwithout giving any account for\novertime. It is true that wage\nworkers are buying certain luxuries\ni today which they did not buy be\nfore. which luxuries are not tabu\nlated lit the official cosf-of-llvtng\nfigures\nArgument for Higher Prices\nAfter labor's lawyer got through\npresenting his case the employer\nstated \"We would not object *o\nstroneli to Increased wages If we\ncould correspondingly in rease the\nprii e of our goods. To do one\nwithout the other, however, ts an\nabsolute impossibility. We would\nbe obliged to shut down. He\nbrough' out the following points:\n(li Not only have the base\nwages mentioned almve gone up\ni irrespective of overtime) but the\nrns' of all materials have, likewise,\ngone up in an amount equal to the\nLittle Steel Formula\n(2 1 Stockholders are getting no\nmore in dividends: yet they must\nbe gi-en a corresponding increase\nin order for them to provide addi\ntional capital which i\u00ab very much\nneeded for reconversion work.\n(3) In answer to labor's com\nplain* about the salaries of officers,\nthe employer stated that their In\ncrease lias been less than the in\ncrease in labor's base wage; fur\nthermore that if all officers work\ned for nothing, it would provide an\nincrease of only from k I:l r la the\nwages of all othwr'mnployes\nForeign Competition\nT did not get into the above dls\ncussion but when asked for my\nI comments. I called attentloii'to the\nfollowing three facts\nfit This country will have huge\nforeign competition in the -years\nahead, from which it was absolute,\nly free during file war. Politicians\nran talk about putting tip higher\ntariff walls, hut this foreign labor\nmust bp given work if we are to\nhate world peace.\nf2) Foreign competition will\nfirst hit special Industries, such as\nthe textile industry; ultimately it\nwill affect all industries.\n(3) For awhile this can be com\npensated for by unemployment In\nffi \u2018Retm\nN V THAN\n'tfA J YOU EVER\nTHOUGHT\nDUHKERS CLUB\nA\nstiraure and living ofT one's war\nsavings; but both of these will\nsome day come to an end and a\ngreat deal of unemployment will\nexist in this country. Only in case\natomic energy should develop Into\na great new industry can such un\nemployment lie prevented.\nA Word to Wage Workers\nBusiness as a whole should con\ntinue good for a few years; but\nlhere is bound to be a big re\nshuffling of jobs This will apply\nto both union and non-union wage\nworkers. For four years the news\npapers have had many columns of\nHeld Wanted\" and only a few in\nclips of \"Positions Wanted' Next\nyear the newspapers will hnvp\nmany columns of \"Positions Want\ned\" and only a few inches of \u201cHelp\nWanted\". Another thing: Your era\nplover has been '.iking anyone lie\ncould get during the war\u2014old peo\nple. children, married women, to\nsay nothing of many inefficient\nworkers.\nNext year this situation will en\ntirely change When you come <o\nwork a year hence, you will find\nthe waiting room full of people\nseeking employment. This means\nthat Inefficient workers w ill be let\ngo and their places substituted by\nmore efficient ones. Therefore. I\nsay to all readers: For heaven's\nsake hang on to your present job.\n(Juit squabbling about wages and\nhours and determine to do better\nwork.\nThink of what is going to happen\na year or two hence. When you\nwere last out of employment it\nwas had enough not to have a pay\nenvelope: but if the proposed wage\nIncreases are granted you may lie\nfaced with not only no pay en\nvelope but with It iflW lit In g I'OSts.\n_ I ~ife\nNO TAKERS\nAnn Arbor